To simplify \(\sqrt{50x}\,\sqrt{2x}\) for \(x>0\), use

\[
\sqrt{50x}\,\sqrt{2x}
=\sqrt{(50x)(2x)}
=\sqrt{100x^2}
=|10x|.
\]

Since \(x>0\), \(|10x|=10x\). 

Answer: \(\displaystyle 10x\).

First write the quotient under one radical and cancel exponents:

\[
\frac{\sqrt{9a^5b^{14}}}{\sqrt{3a^4b^5}}
=\sqrt{\frac{9a^5b^{14}}{3a^4b^5}}
=\sqrt{3\,a^{5-4}b^{14-5}}
=\sqrt{3ab^9}
=\sqrt{3a\,(b^8)\,b}
=b^4\sqrt{3ab}.
\]

Hence the simplified form is 

\[
\boxed{\,b^4\sqrt{3ab}\,}.
\]

To simplify \(\displaystyle \frac{12\sqrt3}{\sqrt2}\):

1. Multiply numerator and denominator by \(\sqrt2\) to rationalize the denominator:
   \[
   \frac{12\sqrt3}{\sqrt2}\;\times\;\frac{\sqrt2}{\sqrt2}
   \;=\;\frac{12\sqrt3\,\sqrt2}{2}
   \;=\;\frac{12\sqrt6}{2}
   \;=\;6\sqrt6.
   \]

So the expression in simplest form is \(\displaystyle 6\sqrt6\).
